Something missing
In curriculum planning . . .
Intense curriculum evaluation sessions took place over vacation
in committee meetings of the presidentially-selected Faculty committee on Educational Policy and Curriculum. In a February re-
rt to the faculty, this committee promised a "sensitive and peraps legislative paper” to be used other vacation for “formal dec
basement, division and individual faculty comment," Thus, the
giverandrtake of faculty over the issue of curriculum change ls at a
peak presently. Whom is this evaluation designed to benefit? is its
aim ll) make the faculty better satisfied with their teaching duties?
That would certainly be fine, but is that the primary aim? Will
new programs created by the study mostly serve President suggest
as a sales tool in fundraising? Or is the goal an educationally pr0<
archive curriculum for the students who actually take the courses?
The curriculum committee has, of course, realized some available methods in attempting to clean student opinion. They requested suggestions (receiving sally little response) and they distributed extensive questionnaires to students and recent clubs. The
questionnaires did elicit what some members of the committee
consider to be a good response for a form of such length. (370 replied out of a student body suffering approximately 1,150. This
does not include clubs.) Committee members The Reporter talked
to expressed the desire to also consult personally with students in
dividually or in groups. While the committee has formal channels
for the gathering of individual faculty and departmental opinion,
no such formal structure exists for similar communication and
feedback with students.
This situation has its origin in President suggest’s discussed
concept of his appointed committee, He believes curriculum matters to be solely a faculty concern. When the committee was
formed, ideas about student representation on it or a parallel student committee were thrown out. A strong senate curriculum committee might have stopped in and detailed recognition but the
student committee was packing — in direction and in firm, con
windows leadership. The student body as a whole has little of which
to be proud in the way it has allowed the study of curriculum
changes to slip through its fingers.
That stage of the study is history now. Yet them il still n
place for student participation before open questions become set
recommendations — especially since the faculty committee seems
reception. There are several possibilities: Students could be
included in curriculum meetings called by the faculty of their
major field. Perhaps faculty members would wish to choose a now
seniors in their department to attend these meetings regularly or
perhaps the meetings should be open. The SGA should incorrect
the concept of a parallel student committee to the faculty’s. The
faculty committee should put a rain on further illustrations until
they have made sure that a structure for Consultation with students
has been put in ettcct. Although student participation should be the
concern of everyone at Grinnell, the responsibility for its image
migration will, in this case, probably rest with SGA ~ thus with
pic MacDoWell and his newly appointed speaker of the senate,
Phil Bertenthal.
